From 44c18eae68ff44b741c10bd80d946b46814d701a Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Thu, 30 Apr 2026 04:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] cython kernel wiring: route production through _native
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Wires the validated Cython kernels into the production feature
extraction pipeline. After this patch, running feature subsets
extraction uses the AOT-compiled C kernels rather than numba.

Workstation verification (user, on nphy-069 9800X3D 16-thread)
showed all 9 kernels byte-equivalent to numba reference and
median 6.15× speedup, with hull (parallel rewrite) achieving
13-110× and border_distances achieving 320-345×.

Strategy: local-alias rebinding
-------------------------------

Each kernel is imported under a local alias prefixed _kern_*
inside a try/except block. The production code calls the alias.
On import failure (Cython extensions not compiled), the except
branch rebinds each alias to the corresponding numba kernel,
emits a RuntimeWarning, and feature extraction continues with
degraded performance instead of crashing.

This pattern was chosen over alternatives:
- Direct import + 11 individual call-site swaps: more diff
  noise, no fallback path
- Module-level monkey-patch of FeatureExtractionMixin methods:
  surprising to readers, affects callers outside this file
- Replacing FeatureExtractionMixin.* in-place: would also
  affect roi_tools/ and other extractors that call these
  kernels — not in scope; those modules can be wired in
  follow-up patches

Deliberate non-changes
----------------------

1. ``bodypart_distance``: pure-Python wrapper that does input
   validation (check_valid_array, check_float, check_valid_boolean),
   converts dtypes, and returns float32. Replacing the call here
   would either lose validation or require duplicating it. Left
   as-is — the validation is real value, and the underlying
   Euclidean distance computation isn't a major cost since this
   call path uses numba already.

2. ``create_shifted_df``: pandas operation, not a numba kernel.
   No Cython equivalent needed.

3. _NATIVE_AVAILABLE module-level flag: set True/False based on
   whether Cython extensions imported successfully. Useful for
   diagnostics; tests can introspect it to know whether the
   speedup path is active.

Defensive fallback rationale
----------------------------

If a user pulls new code without re-running ``pip install -e .``,
the Cython .so files won't exist. A hard ImportError would
break feature extraction entirely. The try/except graceful
fallback:

- Emits warnings.warn(RuntimeWarning) with the fix:
    "Run `pip install -e .` from the repo root to rebuild the
     Cython extensions for full performance."
- Rebinds aliases to numba kernels so feature extraction
  continues working
- Sets _NATIVE_AVAILABLE = False for diagnostics

The warning is emitted at module load (stacklevel=2) so the
user sees it once per process, not on every kernel call.

What changed
------------

1. MODIFIED: mufasa/feature_extractors/feature_subset_kernels.py
   - Renames numba ``jitted_hull`` import to ``_numba_jitted_hull``
     (avoids clash with new ``_kern_hull`` alias)
   - Adds try/except wiring block with 8 _kern_* aliases:
       _kern_angle3pt, _kern_border_distances, _kern_euclid,
       _kern_euclid_roi, _kern_hull, _kern_inside_circle,
       _kern_inside_polygon, _kern_inside_rectangle
   - Swaps 11 production call sites to use the aliases:
       1× angle3pt
       4× hull (perimeter ×3, area ×1)
       1× framewise_euclidean_distance
       1× framewise_euclidean_distance_roi
       1× border_distances
       1× framewise_inside_rectangle_roi
       1× is_inside_circle
       1× framewise_inside_polygon_roi
   - Leaves bodypart_distance and create_shifted_df calls
     unchanged (rationale above)

2. MODIFIED: tests/smoke_cython_full_port_structure.py
   - Old assertion "_native NOT in feature_subset_kernels"
     was correct AT THE TIME of the port patch but is
     invalidated by this wiring patch. Flipped to assert
     _native IS imported, plus checks that the _kern_*
     aliases land and _NATIVE_AVAILABLE is exposed.

3. MODIFIED: tests/smoke_cython_poc_structure.py
   - Same flip. POC's "must NOT yet route to Cython" was
     correct AT THE TIME OF THE POC; this patch is the
     "now route to Cython" moment.

4. NEW: tests/smoke_cython_kernel_wiring.py — 8 cases:
   - try/except import block exists with all 8 kernels
   - Each alias resolves to its numba fallback in except
   - Each alias is INVOKED (not just imported) at least once
     in production call sites — guards against half-wiring
   - _NATIVE_AVAILABLE flag exposed (True/False both present)
   - Fallback emits RuntimeWarning mentioning `pip install`
   - bodypart_distance and create_shifted_df remain unwired
     by design
   - No orphan FeatureExtractionMixin.* / FeatureExtractionSupplemental
     calls outside the fallback block (catches incomplete wiring)
   - jitted_hull import is renamed to _numba_jitted_hull to
     avoid clash with _kern_hull

USER ACTIONS:

1. Apply patch
2. pip install -e .  (no new compilation; the kernel .so files
   from earlier patches are reused)
3. Run a feature extraction job and observe:
   - At process start, no RuntimeWarning means Cython kernels
     are active
   - If you see "Cython kernels unavailable; falling back to
     numba" — extensions need recompiling
4. Compare end-to-end runtime: previously ~hours, now should be
   substantially faster on workloads dominated by border_distances
   or hull. ROI-dominated workloads benefit from inside_rectangle's
   O(N) fix (already in production via patch 50).

Performance expectations on typical 67-video × 50K-frame workload:
- If border_distances or hull is in the feature set, expect
  10-50× total feature-extraction speedup
- If only ROI tests + simple distances, expect ~3-5×
  (limited by per-video overhead: parquet I/O, dataframe ops)

Verified in sandbox:
- All 21 smoke tests pass (3 new + 18 existing)
- AST audit reports zero errors
- compile clean

Cannot be verified in sandbox:
- That the wired kernels produce correct output on real data
  (the sandbox can't run numba or compile Cython)
- The exact end-to-end speedup on the user's workload

Stack now at 53 patches:
  52. hull_parallel_rewrite      (parallel nogil hull)
  53. cython_kernel_wiring       (this patch)
